{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "We are witnessing the rise of an unprecedented phenomenon, the rise of artificially intelligent polls.",
    "Pollsters routinely use them, quantitative political scientists and statisticians have developed their methodology, but the ethical implications of their mass-scale deployment have not been studied.",
    "Allow us a few technical definitions.",
    "The term \"opinion polling\" traditionally refers to the combination of a set of statistical tools, including sampling theory and survey design, used to quantitatively measure opinion-related features of a population of interest from a sample orders of magnitude smaller than this population.",
    "By contrast, artificially intelligent polling allows to make representative inference for deep population categories by bringing in auxiliary information from multiple data sources, via 'regression and post-stratification' algorithms; 'multilevel regression and post-stratification', colloquially known as MrP (Gelman and Little 1997; Park et al. 2004), is the most widely implemented amongst them."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "By contrast, artificially intelligent polling allows to make representative inference for deep population categories by bringing in auxiliary information from multiple data sources, via 'regression and post-stratification' algorithms; 'multilevel regression and post-stratification', colloquially known as MrP (Gelman and Little 1997; Park et al. 2004), is the most widely implemented amongst them."
  ]
